<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">AFFIDAVIT OF ADRIAN SERPA (sworn October 23, 2018)</TI>
<P>I, Adrian Serpa, of the City of Toronto, Province of Ontario, MAKE OATH AND SAY</P>
<P>1. I am an Associate with the law firm of Bell Temple LLP, lawyers for the Applicant, and as such have knowledge of the matters to which I hereinafter depose. Where such knowledge is based upon information and belief, I have identified the source thereof and verily believe the same to be true.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>BACKGROUND</UNDER></TI>
<P>2. On November 17, 2013, Stephen Peter Novak injured himself when he fell off a ladder during a band practice at the premises of an engineering firm, Lakeland Engineering (&ldquo;Lakeland&rdquo;). Lakeland occupies a building owned by 1062220 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>3. At all material times, Sanjay Patel (&ldquo;Patel&rdquo;) was the principal and / or owner of both Lakeland and 1062220 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>4. On January 8, 2015, Novak issued a claim as against Patel, Lakeland and 106220 Ontario Inc. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the Statement of Claim bearing Court File No. CV-15-519329, issued January 8, 2015.</P>
<P>5. There were three insurers potentially liable to indemnify Patel in relation to any damages paid on settlement for the aforementioned incident:
<P1>a. the Applicant, insurer of Lakeland, through CGL coverage available to Patel as a principal of Lakeland. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the subject RSA policy;</P1>
<P1>b. Aviva Insurance (&ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;), insurer of 1062220 Ontario Inc., through CGL coverage available to Patel as its principal. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the Aviva policy; and</P1>
<P1>c. and Intact Insurance (&ldquo;Intact&rdquo;), through a personal homeowner's policy held by Patel in his personal capacity. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the Intact policy.</P1></P>
<P>6. I verily believe that Intact ultimately declined to extend a defence and / or indemnity to Patel under the subject homeowner's policy.</P>
<P>7. Aviva and RSA ultimately agreed to defend Patel in his personal capacity and shared in the costs for same. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the Statement of Defence and Crossclaim of Lakeland, filed on June 2, 2015. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the Statement of Defence and Crossclaim of Patel, filed on July 22, 2015. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the <UNDER>Amended</UNDER> Statement of Defence and Crossclaim of 106220 Ontario Inc., filed January 11, 2016.</P>
<P>8. On January 20, 2016, Patel, by way of Royal and Sun Alliance, brought an application to compel Intact to provide him a defence. After review the &ldquo;Other Insurance&rdquo; clause in the subject Royal and Sun Alliance and Intact insurance policies, the application judge held that Intact had no duty to defend as it was an excesses insurer. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the decision of Justice Mew in <CASEREF><SOC>Patel v. Intact Financial Corporation</SOC></CASEREF>, heard January 20, 2016.</P>
<P>9. The Novak action settled at mediation on February 28, 2017 for an all-inclusive payment of $380,000 (&ldquo;Settlement&rdquo;). The total settlement was split 1/3 ($126,666.66) as between Lakeland, 106220 Ontario Inc. and Patel in his personal capacity. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit are the Minutes and Settlement mid Full and Final Release, dated February 28, 2017.</P>
<P>10. Subsequent to the Settlement, Aviva brought its own application to compel Intact to contribute to costs incurred in defending and settling the claim as against Patel in his personal capacity.</P>
<P>11. The application was heard by Justice Kristjanson on June 7, 2018. In the decision it was noted that the &ldquo;Other Insurance&rdquo; language of the Aviva policy is identical to the RSA policy considered in the previous application. While Intact argued that the Aviva application was <EM>res judicata</EM> and / or an abuse of process, given the previous unsuccessful application of Royal and Sun Alliance, Justice Kristjanson noted at paragraph 29 that the issue of the duty of Intact to <EM>indemnify</EM> had never been addressed. Her Honour went on to decide the issue and ordered Intact to reimburse Aviva for its proportionate share of the settlement and associated defence costs. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of the decision of Justice Kristjanson in <CASEREF><SOC>Aviva Insurance Company v. Intact Insurance Company</SOC></CASEREF>, heard June 7, 2017.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>RELIEF SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. I verily believe that Intact should be compelled to contribute to its proportionate share of the above-noted settlement.</P>
