<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDENT <EM>(Application February 25, 2019)</EM></TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;NATURE OF THE APPLICATION</TI>
<P>1. The Respondent, Intact Financial Corporation (&ldquo;Intact&rdquo;), takes the position that this Application is an abuse of process and should be dismissed under the doctrines of <EM>res judicata</EM> and/or issue estoppel.</P>
<P>2. The Applicant, Royal &amp; Sun Alliance Insurance Company (&ldquo;RSA&rdquo;) brought a previous Application against Intact, seeking an order that Intact had a duty to defend and indemnify RSA with respect to the same loss, which Application was heard on January 20, 2016. The Honourable Justice Graeme Mew held that the Intact Policy was excess to the RSA policy, and therefore the Intact policy did not come into play. Justice Mew's decision is dated January 20, 2016 (&ldquo;the decision&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. This Application is an abuse of process because RSA is attempting to re-litigate the issues which were already decided by Justice Mew.</P>
<P>4. If RSA wanted to dispute the decision, the proper procedure would have been to file an Appeal. RSA chose not to do so.</P>
<P>5. The Respondent seeks the following:
<P1>(a) An Order dismissing the Application; and,</P1>
<P1>(b) Costs of responding to this Application on a substantial indemnity scale.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Underlying Action</EM></TI>
<P>6. The Statement of Claim in the underlying action was issued on January 8, 2015 (the &ldquo;Underlying Action&rdquo;). The Statement of Claim alleges that the Plaintiff, Stephen Peter Novak, suffered personal injuries when he fell off a ladder while he was at the business premises owned and operated by Sanjay Patel (&ldquo;Patel&rdquo;).
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Statement of Claim, para. 6</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2A</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>7. The Defendants in the Statement of Claim were Patel, Lakeland Engineering Ltd. and 1062220 Ontario Inc. Patel is a principal of Lakeland Engineering and 1062220 Ontario Inc.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Statement of Claim, paras. 3&ndash;6</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2A</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>8. Patel was defended by Aviva and RSA in the Underlying Action. RSA and Aviva each appointed counsel which entered a Statement of Defence on Patel's behalf.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Affidavit of Adrian Serpa, para. 7</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Previous Coverage Application Brought by RSA</EM></TI>
<P>9. RSA issued a previous Coverage Application on September 3, 2015, bearing Court File No. CV-15-535694 (the &ldquo;Previous Coverage Application&rdquo;), seeking the following relief:
<P1>i. A declaration that Intact has a duty to defend Patel;</P1>
<P1><BOLD>ii. A declaration that Intact had a duty to indemnify Patel;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>iii. An Order requiring Intact to assume the defence of Patel; and,</P1>
<P1>iv. An Order that Intact indemnify Patel for all legal costs incurred.
<P2><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P3><BOLD>Notice of Application, Court File CV-15-535694, page 3</BOLD></P3>
<P3><BOLD>Responding Application Record, Tab 1</BOLD></P3></P2></P1></P>
<P>10. The Previous Coverage Application was brought in Patel's name by counsel appointed by RSA, which is the same law firm bringing the within application.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Notice of Application, Court File CV-15-535694 page 3</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Responding Application Record, Tab 1</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>11. The Previous Coverage Application was heard on January 20, 2016 before the Honourable Justice Graeme Mew. Justice Mew held that the Intact Policy was triggered by the claims in the Underlying Action, but that the Intact Policy was excess to the RSA Policy pursuant to an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy. The decision reads, in part, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[7] There is, however, an important limiting factor. The respondent's policy provides that if an insured has &ldquo;other insurance which applies to a loss or claim&rdquo; the respondent's policy &ldquo;will be considered excess insurance&rdquo; and will not respond &ldquo;until the amount of such other insurance is used up.&rdquo;</P>
<P>18] The applicant is being defended by RSA in the main action. He is not (yet) being defended on the cross-claims, although it is not apparent from the record why this is so.</P>
<P>[9] The RSA policy has an &ldquo;Other Insurance&rdquo; provision, which renders the RSA policy primary unless there is another policy which is also primary, or if the other insurance is &ldquo;Property Insurance&rdquo;, a term not defined in the RSA policy.</P>
<P>[10] In my view, as the coverage available to the applicant under the respondent's policy vis-a-vis the Novak claim falls under the policy's liability coverage, the fact that it also insures the applicant's property does not make the whole policy &ldquo;Property Insurance&rdquo; for the purposes of the RSA &ldquo;Other Insurance&rdquo; condition,</P>
<P>[11] <BOLD><UNDER>As a result, the respondent's [Intact] policy is excess to the RSA policy. The coverage provided by the respondent's policy only becomes available once the RSA coverage (and any other primary coverage available to the applicant) is used up.</UNDER></BOLD> As a result, no obligation for the respondent to defend has arisen yet. See: <CASEREF><SOC>Axa v. Dominion</SOC><YEAR>2004</YEAR><CITE>73 O.R. (3d) 391</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Chretien v. Ryder Truck</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 5347</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Endorsement Of Justice Mew, paras. 7&ndash;11</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2H</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>12. In the within Application, RSA has suggested that Justice Mew acted under his own initiative, &ldquo;without explanation&rdquo;, to compare the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses in the respective policies. In actuality, Intact had opposed the Application on the these grounds. Intact raised the issue in the Previous Coverage Application that the Intact Policy was excess in its factum. This issue was also argued by both sides during oral submissions. RSA had every opportunity to dispute the application of the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause at the previous Application.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Responding Factum, Court File CV-15-535694, paras. 46&ndash;52</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Responding Application Record, Tab 2</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>13. Justice Mew was able to reconcile the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses and he found that they did not cancel each other out. In doing so, Justice Mew cited that the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy expressly stated that it was excess, whereas, the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the RSA Policy stated that it was primary.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Endorsement Of Justice Mew, paras. 7&ndash;11</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2H</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>14. More than 1 year after the Previous Coverage Application was decided, The Underlying Action settled at a private mediation on February 28, 2017 for $380,000.00. The settlement was for less than the RSA policy limits of $2,000,000.00. Intact did not attend the mediation, having already obtained a Decision from Justice Mew that the Intact Policy was excess to the RSA policy.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Affidavit of Adrian Serpa, para. 9</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The <EM>Respective</EM> Insurance Policies</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>(i)</N><TI>The Intact Homeowner's Policy</TI>
<P>15. At all material times, Patel was insured by Intact under a homeowner's policy, which provided coverage for third party liability arising out of Patel's personal actions anywhere in the world.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Intact Policy</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2D</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>16. The Respondent does not dispute that the Intact Policy provided coverage for the claims in the Underlying Action. This issue was already decided by Justice Mew.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Endorsement of Justice Mew, dated January 20, 2016</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2H</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>17. The Homeowner's Policy contains an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause under Exclusions, Section II, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Insurance Under More Than One Policy</P>
<P>If you have other insurance which applies to a loss or claim, or would have applied if this policy did not exist, this policy will be considered excess insurance and we will not pay any loss or claim until the amount of such other insurance is used up.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Intact Policy, page 12</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2D</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(ii)</N><TI>The RSA Commercial General Liability Policy</TI>
<P>18. At all material times, Patel and Lakeland Engineering, were insured under the RSA Policy, which provided liability coverage for bodily injury claims with policy limits of $2.0 million (the &ldquo;RSA Policy&rdquo;).
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>RSA Policy, page 15</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2B</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>19. The RSA Policy contains an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause at section 9 of Sub-Section 4&mdash;Commercial General Liability Conditions, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Other Insurance</P>
<P>If other valid and collectible insurance is available to the insured for a loss we cover under Coverage A, B, D or F of Section III, our obligations are limited as follows:</P>
<P>(a) PRIMARY INSURANCE</P>
<P>This insurance is primary except when (b) applies. If this insurance is primary, our obligations are not affected unless any of the other insurance is also primary. Then, we will share with all other insurance by the method described in (c) below.</P>
<P>(b) EXCESS INSURANCE</P>
<P>This is insurance is excess over:
<P1>(1) Any of the other insurance, whether primary, excess, contingency or on any other basis:
<QUOTE><P>That is Property Insurance which also includes but is not limited to Builder's Risk, Installation Floater or similar coverage for &ldquo;your work&rdquo; or for premises of other rented to you or occupied by you;
<P1>(a) If the loss arises out of the maintenance or use of watercraft to the extent not subject to Exclusions(e) of Coverage A.</P1></P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>(2) Any other primary insurance available to you covering liability for &ldquo;compensatory damages&rdquo; arising out of the premises or operations or products-completed operations for which you have been added as an additional insured by attachment of an endorsement.</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>RSA Policy, pages 40-41</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2B</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;THE ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>20. The issue to be determined in this application is whether the Respondent owes a duty to indemnify the Applicant with respect to the claims in the Underlying Action. In order to answer this question, the following issues must be addressed:
<P1>i. Should the Application be dismissed because it is <EM>res judicata</EM> and/or an abuse of process?</P1>
<P1>ii. If the Application is not <EM>res judicata</EM> and/or an abuse of process, did Justice Mew err in deciding that the Intact Policy was excess?</P1>
<P1>iii. Is RSA entitled to equitable relief from Intact?</P1></P>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>#1:</N><TI>RES JUDICATA / ABUSE OF PROCESS</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Law</EM></TI>
<P>21. The Respondent submits that the Application should be dismissed, as it is <EM>res judicata</EM>. Specifically, the Respondent relies on the branch of <EM>res judicata</EM> known as issue estoppel, which prevents a party from litigating an issue that has already been decided in a previous proceeding.</P>
<P>22. The doctrine of issue estoppel has three elements:
<P1>1. The same question has been decided;</P1>
<P1>2. The prior judicial decision was final; and</P1>
<P1>3. The parties, or their privies, must be the same.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Angle v. Minister of National Revenue</SOC><CITE>[1975] 2 S.C.R. 248</CITE><PAGENUM>at 254</PAGENUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 1</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>23. The Supreme Court has held that the three elements of issue estoppel should not be applied in a rigid or mechanical fashion. The underlying purpose is to balance the public interest of the finality of litigation with the public interest that justice is done.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Danyluk v. Ainsworth Technologies Inc.</SOC><CITE>2001 SCC 44</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 2</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>24. The Supreme Court has held that, even where issue estoppel is not available because the parties are not exactly the same, the Court has discretion to dismiss a claim under the doctrine of abuse of process in order to prevent a party from re-litigating an issue that has already been decided, or ought reasonably to have been raised in earlier proceedings.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Toronto v. C.U.P.E. Local 79</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 63</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 3</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>25. The Supreme Court has endorsed the use of the doctrine of abuse of process to prevent relitigation, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Canadian courts have applied the doctrine of abuse of process to preclude relitigation in circumstances where the strict requirements of issue estoppel (typically the privity/mutuality requirements) are not met, but where allowing the litigation to proceed would nonetheless violate such principles as judicial economy, consistency, finality and the integrity of the administration of justice...</P>
<P>The attraction of the doctrine of abuse of process is that it is unencumbered by the specific requirements of res judicata while offering the discretion to prevent relitigation, essentially for the purpose of preserving the integrity of the court's process.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Toronto v. C.U.P.E. Local 79</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 63</CITE><PARANUM>37, 42</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 3</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>26. The Respondent submits that issue estoppel ought to apply in the within case [because all three of the preconditions have been met: The same issue has been decided; the decision was final; and the parties are the same.</P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Same Issue Has Been Decided</EM></TI>
<P>27. One of the issues decided in the Previous Coverage Application was that the Intact Policy was excess to the RSA Policy.</P>
<P>28. By deciding that the Intact Policy was excess, Justice Mew already decided that the Intact Policy cannot come into play to unless and until RSA's policy limits are used up. Therefore, the issue of whether Intact has a duty to indemnify has already been decided.</P>
<P>29. Where a policy is excess, there is no distinction between a duty to defend and a duty to indemnify. A policy cannot be excess for the purposes of a duty to defend, but not excess for a duty to indemnify. In <CASEREF><SOC>Axa v. Dominion</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court of Appeal discussed the interplay between a duty to defend, a duty to indemnify and an excess clause:
<QUOTE><P>Axa contends that the application judge erred by concluding that Dominion's excess coverage provision applied to both its duty to defend and its duty to indemnify. Axa submits that if it applies at all, it applies only to the duty to indemnify for losses above $1 million; it does not apply to Dominion's duty to defend Dr. Isen which, asserts Axa, is a primary obligation.</P>
<P>The application judge rejected Axa's argument. He stated:
<QUOTE><P>Dominion has no obligation to defend until it is determined that AXA's limits have been used up. If that occurs, Dominion is liable to pay the pro rata share of the defence costs. If there are special circumstances, further directions may be sought.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>I agree. Dominion's policy states that it &ldquo;will not pay any loss or <EM>claim</EM> until the amount of such other insurance is used up&rdquo; (emphasis added). <BOLD><UNDER>Axa's argument amounts to an attempt to create a distinction, which does not appear in the policy, between a claim for indemnity and a claim for a defence. The excess insurance provision does not make this distinction, but refers only to a claim or a loss covered by other insurance.</UNDER></BOLD> <BOLD><UNDER>Since the claim for a defence is covered by Axa's policy, Dominion's policy Is excess to Axa's policy in respect of both Dr. Isen's claim for indemnity and his claim for a defence.</UNDER></BOLD> On the plain wording of Dominion's policy, Dominion does not have to pay any claim for defence costs until Axa's obligation to defend is &ldquo;used up&rdquo;. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Axa Insurance v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 4513</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 26&ndash;28</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Brief of Authorities, Tab 4</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>30. Justice Mew's decision was not limited to the issue of duty to defend and contribution to defence costs. As addressed in <CASEREF><SOC>AXA v. Dominion</SOC></CASEREF>, the decision that the Intact Policy was excess applies to both the duty to defend <BOLD><UNDER>and</UNDER></BOLD> the duty to indemnify.</P>
<P>31. Justice Mew decided that Intact did not have a duty to indemnify Patel unless the policy limits of the RSA Policy (and any other primary coverage) was used up. As the Underlying Action settled for less than the policy limits of the RSA Policy, the Intact Policy cannot come into play, based on Justice Mew's decision.</P>
<P>32. In the within Application, the Applicants are arguing that Justice Mew's decision was incorrect. The correctness of Justice Mew's decision is not open for debate in the within Application. There was no appeal.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Decision Was Final</EM></TI>
<P>33. There is no question that the decision of Justice Mew was final and was not appealed.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>(iii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Parties Are The Same</EM></TI>
<P>34. The Respondent submits that the parties to the Applications are the same. The Previous Coverage Application was brought by RSA in Patel's name. The Application was brought for RSA's benefit. Patel had no interest in the outcome of the Application.</P>
<P>35. The Respondent submits that RSA was a de facto party and/or a privy of Patel in the Previous Coverage Application and therefore, the same party requirement of issue estoppel is met.</P>
<P>36. The concept of privity is elastic. The determination of whether there is privity must be made on a case-by-case basis. Privity is established where the decision rendered against one should be binding on the other.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Martinez de Morales v. LaFontaine-Rish Medical Group Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2009 CanLII 31991</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 21</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 5</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<BLOCK6><TI>Abuse of Process</TI>
<P>37. Even if the requirements of issue estoppel are not technically met because the parties are not exactly the same, the Respondent submits that the Court should dismiss the Application under the doctrine of abuse of process in order to prevent re-litigation.</P>
<P>38. The application of the doctrine of abuse of process to prevent re-litigation allows the Court to maintain the integrity of the adjudicative process by avoiding inconsistent results in separate proceedings, which the Supreme Court has found would undermine the credibility of the entire judicial process.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Toronto v. C.U.P.E. Local 79</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 63</CITE><PARANUM>51</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 3</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>39. In the within case, it would be unfair to allow RSA to succeed on the within Application given Justice Mew's previous decision; As a result of Justice Mew's decision, Intact had a reasonable belief that the Policy was excess and therefore chose not to participate in the action or attend at the mediation. Intact would be prejudiced if forced to indemnify RSA for a settlement reached without Intact's input.</P></BLOCK6></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>#2:</N><TI>DID JUSTICE MEW ERR IN DECIDING THAT THE INTACT POLICY WAS EXCESS TO THE RSA POLICY</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>a)</EM></N><TI><EM>Justice Mew did not Err by Failing to Consider</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance v. Lombard</SOC></CASEREF></TI>
<P>40. The Respondent respectfully takes the position that this Application is not the proper forum to dispute whether or not Justice Mew erred in deciding that the Intact Policy was excess. However, if this Honourable Court decides that this issue ought to be re-litigated, the Respondent submits that Justice Mew did not err. More specifically, Justice Mew did not err by failing to cite the Supreme Court of Canada Decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance v. Lombard Canada Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF></P>
<P>41. Whether or not Justice Mew considered a particular case is an issue that could have been dealt with during an appeal, not a separate Application.</P>
<P>42. Regardless, the Respondent denies that <CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance v. Lombard</SOC></CASEREF>, was applicable to the issues in the Previous Coverage Application, as has been alleged by RSA.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance Corp. v. Lombardi</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 48</CITE></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 6</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>43. The <CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance v. Lombard</SOC></CASEREF> decision stands for the principle that where two insurance policies contain competing &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses <BOLD><EM>which cannot be reconciled</EM>,</BOLD> the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses cancel each other out and the Court should apply the doctrine of equitable contribution. The first step is to determine if the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses can be reconciled. Only where there is a &ldquo;true impasse&rdquo; does the law of equitable contribution come into play. If the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses can be reconciled, equitable contribution is not available.</P>
<P>44. The <EM>Family Insurance</EM> case is not part of an analysis into interpreting or applying an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance Corp. v. Lombard</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 48</CITE><PARANUM>32&ndash;34</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 6</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>45. The thrust of the <EM>Family Insurance</EM> decision was addressed by the Ontario Court of Appeal in the case of <CASEREF><SOC>McKenzie v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Company</SOC></CASEREF>. In that case, a primary insurer argued that an excess insurer should contribute to defence costs pursuant to the doctrine of equitable contribution. The Ontario Court of Appeal clarified that the <EM>Family Insurance</EM> decision is not applicable where there are &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses <BOLD>which can be reconciled.</BOLD> In circumstances where the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses can be reconciled (for example, if one policy is primary and one policy is excess), equitable contribution does <BOLD><UNDER>not</UNDER></BOLD> come into play. The Court of Appeal explained the analysis as follows:
<QUOTE><P>While both policies provide similarly worded other insurance clauses, they will only effectively cancel one another out if, to use the language of Family Insurance, supra, at para. 28, the parties were under &ldquo;coordinate obligation to make good the loss&rdquo;. In this case there can be no doubt that the State Family PLUP, by its language, was written in contemplation of there being other underlying insurance coverage. The Dominion policy was not; its coverage language makes it clear that the intention was that it provide primary insurance. These are not policies of coordinate obligation.</P>
<P>To be clear, I respectfully disagree with the respondent Dominion's submission, and the application judge's conclusion, that the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses in the PLUP and the home owner's policy are irreconcilable. Such a conclusion is only possible where the policies in question cover the same level of risk. The two policies in issue before this court do not. The PLUP is a true umbrella policy while the homeowner's policy is a primary policy, which pays first dollar insurance coverage unless there is other insurance. The reference to &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; in a primary policy can only reasonably refer to other primary insurance. Were it otherwise, the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses in primary policies would make them excess or umbrella policies, which is clearly not the intent of a primary policy.</P>
<P>Second, in my view, both the application judge and the respondent Dominion have misinterpreted Family Insurance, supra. It seems to me that if the Supreme Court of Canada had intended to do away with any distinction among primary, excess and/or umbrella policies of insurance it would have done so in clear and express language to that effect.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>As I have said, in my view the reasoning in Family Insurance simply does not apply in the circumstances of this case where, as I discussed above, the relevant policies of insurance provide different layers of coverage, or, stated another way, where the contest is between a primary insurer and an excess or umbrella insurer. Unlike the situation in Family Insurance, we are not here concerned with two primary policies (leaving the boat owner policy aside) with similar &ldquo;other insurance clauses&rdquo;.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Reference:</EM></BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>McKenzie v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Co. et al.</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 480</CITE><PARANUM>20&ndash;22, 29</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 7</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>46. There is no authority for the Applicant's argument that two insurance policies must be &ldquo;overlapping&rdquo; in order for an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause to apply. Neither the Supreme Court in <EM>Family Insurance</EM>, nor the Ontario Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>McKenzie v. Dominion</SOC></CASEREF>, applied such a test No authorities have been cited by the Applicant which supports this position.</P>
<P>47. Justice Mew reconciled the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses in the Intact Policy and the RSA Policy. He found that the &ldquo;Other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy took effect over the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the RSA Policy. Accordingly, there was no need to consider the doctrine of equitable contribution or the <EM>Family Insurance</EM> decision.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>b)</EM></N><TI><EM>Justice Mew did not err in his interpretation of the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clauses</EM></TI>
<P>48. An excess insurer has no obligation to indemnify a primary insurer until the primary insurer's policy limits are &ldquo;used up&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Axa Insurance v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 4513</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 26&ndash;28</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Brief of Authorities, Tab 4</BOLD></P2>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Chretien v. Ryder Truck Rental Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 5347</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 13</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Brief of Authorities, Tab 8</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>49. There is no requirement that two polices be &ldquo;overlapping&rdquo; in order for an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause to apply. For example, in the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Axa v. Dominion</SOC></CASEREF>, a claim arose out of personal injury which occurred while an Individual was using a bungee cord to secure a Cushion to a boat which was hitched to a car trailer. The bungee cord detached and struck his friend in the eye. There were three policies which potentially covered the loss: a motor vehicle liability policy, a boat liability policy and a homeowner's policy. Clearly, these policies are not entirely overlapping, as they cover separate risks. The boat policy acknowledged that its coverage was triggered but argued that it was excess to the motor vehicle liability policy pursuant to an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause. The Court agreed. In determining that the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the boat policy applied to make it excess, the Court of Appeal did not address or consider whether the policies were &ldquo;overlapping&rdquo;. In other words, this is not a relevant consideration in the analysis of whether an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause applies.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Axa Insurance v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 4513</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Brief of Authorities, Tab 4</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>50. In <CASEREF><SOC>Axa v. Dominion</SOC></CASEREF>, The Court of Appeal found that the boat policy was excess to a motor vehicle liability policy based on an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause, which read as follows:
<QUOTE><P>If you have other insurance not insured with us which applies to a loss or claim ... our policy will be considered excess insurance and we will not pay any loss or claim until the amount of such other insurance is used up.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Axa Insurance v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 4513</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>para. 21</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Brief of Authorities, Tab 4</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>51. In the within case, the Intact Policy contains the following &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause, which is very similar to the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause of the boat policy discussed in <CASEREF><SOC>Axa v. Dominion</SOC></CASEREF>. The relevant portion of the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy states:
<QUOTE><P>If you have other insurance which applies to a loss or claim, or would have applied if this policy did not exist, this policy will be considered excess insurance and we will not pay any loss or claim until the amount of such other insurance is used up.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Homeowner's Policy, page 12</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Application Record, Tab 2D</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>52. In contrast, The RSA Policy contains an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause, which expressly stipulates that it is primary, unless criteria which are no currently present, are met:
<P1>(a) PRIMARY INSURANCE
<QUOTE><P>This insurance is primary except when (b) applies. If this insurance is primary, our obligations are not affected unless any of the other insurance is also primary. Then, we will share with all other insurance by the method described in (c) below.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>(b) EXCESS INSURANCE
<QUOTE><P>This is insurance is excess over:
<P1>(1) Any of the other insurance, whether primary, excess, contingency or on any other basis:
<QUOTE><P>That is Property Insurance which also includes but is not limited to Builder's Risk, Installation Floater or similar coverage for &ldquo;your work&rdquo; or for premises of other rented to you or occupied by you;
<P1>(a) If the loss arises out of the maintenance or use of watercraft to the extent not subject to Exclusions(e) of Coverage A.</P1></P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>(2) Any other primary insurance available to you covering liability for &ldquo;compensatory damages&rdquo; arising out of the premises or operations or products-completed operations for which you have been added as an additional insured by attachment of an endorsement.</P1></P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>RSA Policy, pages 40-41</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Responding Application Record, Tab 2B</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>53. A plain reading of the terms of the RSA Policy reveals that the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause has the effect of making the RSA Policy primary to any coverage that is not properly insurance or coverage arising out of the insured premises. The Intact Policy provides coverage for liability insurance which is not property insurance. Consequently, the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy clearly applies, thereby making the RSA Policy primary coverage in respect of this loss.</P>
<P>54. As a result of the excess clause in the Intact Policy, the Respondent does not have a duty to indemnify unless and until the policy limits of the RSA Policy are used up, which is impossible now that the claim settled for well under the available limits.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>#3:</N><TI>IS RSA ENTITLED TO EQUITABLE RELIEF?</TI>
<P>55. The Respondent disputes that the Applicant should be entitled to equitable relief.</P>
<P>56. In <CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance Corp. v. Lombard</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada considered the circumstances where an insurer can seek indemnification from another insurer who covers the same risk pursuant to the doctrine of equitable contribution. The doctrine is founded on the general principle that parties under a &ldquo;coordinate liability&rdquo; to make good a loss must share that burden pro rata. Where two policies do not cover the same risk (as RSA alleges is the case here), then equitable contribution is not available.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance Corp. v. Lombard</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 48</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 6</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>57. The test for equitable contribution is set out in the 6 Ivamy Principles, originally cited in Ivamy's <EM>General Principles of Insurance Law</EM>. The 6 Ivamy Principles are as follows:
<P1>i. All the policies concerned must comprise the same subject matter</P1>
<P1>ii. All the polices must be effected against the same peril</P1>
<P1>iii. All the policies must be effected by or on behalf of the same assured</P1>
<P1>iv. All the polices must be in force at the time of the loss</P1>
<P1>v. All the polices must be legal contracts of insurance</P1>
<P1>vi. No policy must contain any stipulation by which it is excluded from contribution (such as an &ldquo;other insurance clause&rdquo;)</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Family Insurance Corp. v. Lombard</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 48</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tab 6</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>58. The Ivamy Principles are not a precondition to the application of an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause. In fact, the 6th of the Ivamy Principles would include a consideration of whether an &ldquo;other insurance clause&rdquo; was present (criteria vi).</P>
<P>59. The Ivamy Principles set out 6 preconditions which must be met in order for an Insurer to seek equitable contribution from another insurer, just as RSA is seeking equitable contribution from Intact in the within Application.</P>
<P>60. The Ivamy Principles define the parameters when one insurer can seek indemnification from another insurer which covers the same risk. The Ivamy Principles do not dictate the circumstances when an insurer can invoke an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause.</P>
<P>61. Where the 6 Ivamy principles are not met (for example because an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause excludes contribution) an insurer is not entitled to equitable contribution from another insurer which covers the same risk.</P>
<P>62. For example, in the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Universities Reciprocal Insurance Exchange v. Halwell Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF>, a CGL insurer sought equitable contribution from a home insurer which allegedly insured the same risk. The Court found that the CGL insurer was not entitled to equitable contribution because the homeowner's insurer had an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause which applied. Whether or not the policies were overlapping was not relevant. This is exactly the situation in the case at bar. If the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy applies (and Justice Mew already decided it does), RSA is not entitled to equitable contribution.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Universities Reciprocal Insurance (CURIE) v. Halwell Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>1998 CarswellOnt 4932</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 28&ndash;30, aff'd by</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Universities Reciprocal Insurance (CURIE) v. Halwell Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2002 CarswellOnt 2766</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 34, 36-37</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Brief of Authorities of the Respondent, Tabs 9 &amp; 10</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>63. In the present case, Justice Mew has already determined that the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy <BOLD>can be reconciled</BOLD> with the &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the RSA Policy, just as was the case in <CASEREF><SOC>CURIE v. Halwell</SOC></CASEREF>. Therefore, equitable contribution does <BOLD><UNDER>not</UNDER></BOLD> apply.</P>
<P>64. Even if the principles of equitable contribution were to apply, the Applicants must prove that that the 6 Ivamy Principles have been met in order to seek equitable contribution from Intact. The Applicant's submission in their factum that the 6 Ivamy Principles do not apply supports the Respondent's position and precludes Aviva's right to seek equitable contribution.</P>
<P>65. Finally, the Respondent submits that there are no other equitable grounds which would entitle RSA to relief from Intact.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>66. In summary, the Respondent submits that the Application should be dismissed on the grounds the Application is <EM>res judicata</EM> and/or an abuse of process.</P>
<P>67. In the alternative, the Respondent submits that it does not have a duty to indemnify the Applicant due to the existence of an &ldquo;other insurance&rdquo; clause in the Intact Policy.</P>
<P>68. The Respondent seeks the following:
<P1>(a) An Order dismissing the Application;</P1>
<P1>(b) Costs of responding to this Application on a substantial indemnity scale.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS 8<SUP>th</SUP> DAY OF FEBRUARY 2019</P>
